<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-02-10T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-02-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="407" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">837.61351/2–1048: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-02-10T13:00:00-05:00">February
                                    10, 1948—1 p. m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>169. Meeting of Cuban sugar leaders and Belt with President Grau
                            yesterday afternoon apparently agreed to sell one million tons at 4
                            cents which Marshall reportedly accepted by phone. Important
                            reservation, however, that army can move only through deep ports still
                            unacceptable Cuba.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>